    .content.container
      h1 Hi!
      h5 It looks like you are running the "pomegranate-docker" container without mounting a volume in the container.
      p Thats ok, we added this default content for just that reason. When you mount your own content,
        | it will totally overwrite the default, so dont worry about that at all.

      p Assuming you have already run something like this:

      pre $ docker run -d -p 8080:8080 paperelectron/pomegranate-docker

      p You are going to want to add a directory on your docker host, call it 'my_content' or whatever floats your boat.
        | Add your routes, views, models, etc, to 'my_content', then start the 'paperelectron/pomegranate-docker' container
        | using something like this:

      pre docker run -d -p 8080:8080 \
        | -v ~/pomegranate/my_content:/var/pom/content \
        | paperelectron/pomegranate-docker

      p A neat trick is to, is to store all of your pomegranate routes, models, views, etc. in a sepatate git repo.
        | When developing locally, pass the path to this location to a pomegranite instance. Then when you want to update
        | the docker container, simply merge your changes then stop and restart the 'paperelectron/pomegranate-docker'
        | container.
